textDisplay: I return to this video more often than I should. It was a video that was recommended to me, probably because I watched a lot of videos about how Philadelphia handled the Yellow Fever Epidemic of 1793 and how the city mishandled the Spanish Flu Pandemic of 1918. When I first watched this video, it inspired me to watch the film 'Contagion' again, and of course like most people at that time I could not, would not, believe that this would become the horror that it eventually became. The first months of 2020 are still so fresh in my mind. I remember the larger, cultural things. The wildfires; the winning of the film 'Parasite;' Ricky Gervais roasting Hollywood; Kobe Bryant... But, more than that, clearer than things that happened yesterday, I remember the smaller, personal things. I'd just hired a new employee to my team; we were doing amazing at work with our reputation as the A-Team office; I was replaying 'Assassin's Creed Rogue' and had just watched 'Last of the Mohicans' for the first time since childhood; my artwork was something I looked forward to doing again; I felt like I was getting myself together, mentally, emotionally, and financially. And then this was posted, and I remember being more curious than alarmed. Even as the weeks passed, I wasn't as afraid as I guess I should have been. Then Wuhan went into lockdown, and I remember saying to my friend at work that Wuhan is around five times the size of Philadelphia. The videos showing the emptied streets, the shuttered seafood market where this was allegedly born, and so many videos coming out of the city showing people being forced from their apartments, or forced into ambulances, that one doctor screaming at his boss, the nurse crying out in anguish. But it was all still so far away. It was 2020, I said to myself, and surely we're well beyond the times in which a pandemic could spread like in the documentaries or fictional films I'd watched. The Diamond Princess cruise ship was alarming but I remember feeling so self-righteous and insensitive, like 'well, why would you go on a cruise at a time like this.' Then the virus followed a similar but not exact trajectory as the Black Death, traveling through Iran and slamming into Italy. Cases detected within nursing homes in the United States, on the West Coast and then in New York, before a case finally showed itself in Philadelphia. My best friend called me in panic that her state, New Jersey, was shutting down. Philly followed suit. It all still sounds so surreal and fictional, and that I remember it all so well... The only other time I feel a kind of twisted moment-by-moment nostalgia like this is when I remember the morning of September 11, 2001. Watching this video feels like watching videos of New York on September 10th, 2001. None of us can really explain what this feeling is, but most of us feel it, like a sudden fragrance that reminds us of childhood but we can't detect where it's from. I'm sorry to have rambled, but I felt compelled to ramble.
